  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2025 by Peter Lang Verlag, Samantha Vanderslott's <em>Pro-vax</em> is an early-career contribution to the medical humanities that sits squarely within the global conversation on vaccine acceptance and public health communication. Although citation evidence is still accumulating, the book has already attracted scholarly attention from active researchers working across Southeast Asia and South Asia, and its citation percentile places it among the higher-performing works of comparable age in its field.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\"><em>Pro-vax</em> appears as the fourth volume in Peter Lang's <em>Medical Humanities: Criticism and Creativity</em> series, joining titles that examine embodied illness narratives, creative mobility practices, and breast cancer experience. The series situates humanistic and critical perspectives alongside empirical public health concerns, and Vanderslott's contribution extends that project into the contested terrain of vaccine advocacy and hesitancy. The book's strong alignment with UN Sustainable Development Goal 3 \u2014 Good Health and Well-being \u2014 signals that its arguments carry direct relevance to ongoing global health policy debates, particularly around immunisation equity and public trust in health institutions.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The most concrete early indicator of scholarly uptake is a citation recorded in 2026 in <em>PLOS Global Public Health</em>, a peer-reviewed open-access journal with broad reach in global health research. The citing study examines COVID-19 vaccine acceptance and uptake across Indonesia, Nepal, and Vietnam through qualitative and thematic analysis, drawing on institutional expertise from the University of Oxford, Oxford University Clinical Research Units in Vietnam and Indonesia, the University of Indonesia, Kathmandu University, and the Hospital for Tropical Diseases. That this geographically diverse, multi-institutional team reached for <em>Pro-vax</em> as a reference point \u2014 even before the book completed its first full year of circulation \u2014 suggests Vanderslott's framing is speaking to researchers grappling with real-world challenges in vaccine communication and psychological intervention design.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of library reach, the book has been catalogued across several institutions, with holdings recorded in WorldCat under the subject heading of public health. This early library presence is consistent with adoption potential for graduate courses in medical humanities, science and technology studies, and public health communication \u2014 disciplinary areas where the interplay of cultural meaning-making and health behaviour is increasingly central to the curriculum.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">It is worth noting that citation trajectories for scholarly monographs in the humanities and social sciences typically unfold over a longer horizon than journal articles, and <em>Pro-vax</em> has only just entered scholarly circulation. The single citation on record should therefore be read as a meaningful early signal rather than a complete picture. Its placement in the 85th percentile for works of comparable type and vintage reinforces this reading. As debates over vaccine hesitancy, health communication strategy, and the social dimensions of immunisation continue to intensify globally, <em>Pro-vax</em> is well positioned to accumulate influence across both humanistic scholarship and applied public health research.</p>",
